<methodology slug="agentic-ai-product-development">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-manager</domain>
    <summary>Product methodology for autonomous AI systems. Replaces MVP with MVI; scope by intelligence level, not feature count. Requires goal states, actions, human checkpoints, escalation-first design.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>agentic-ai</tag>
      <tag>product-spec</tag>
      <tag>mvi</tag>
      <tag>goal-achievement</tag>
      <tag>autonomous-systems</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Agentic AI Product Development</title>
    <summary>A product methodology for designing and shipping autonomous AI systems — agents that act toward a goal without user-triggering each step. Replaces the MVP (Minimum Viable Product) frame with MVI (Minimum Viable Intelligence): scope is determined by the intelligence level the system must achieve, not by feature count. Every spec must enumerate autonomous actions explicitly, define machine-verifiable goal states, and document the human-in-the-loop model before engineering starts.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Traditional AI feature specs describe behavior in natural language ("the agent will handle complex cases"), which is not implementable. Agentic products require a different type of success metric (goal achievement rate, autonomy ratio, cost-per-task) and a different failure model (edge-case recovery paths, behavioral regression tests). 40% of agentic pilots fail to productionize — the failure point is usually not the model but the absence of a production-grade escalation path.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Writing a product spec where the core delivery mechanism is an autonomous agent (not a user-triggered model call)</item>
        <item>Defining MVI scope: which capabilities are core intelligence vs deferred to v2</item>
        <item>Choosing success metrics for an agentic feature (goal achievement rate, escalation rate, autonomy ratio, cost-per-task)</item>
        <item>Documenting the human-in-the-loop model for stakeholders</item>
        <item>Deciding which use cases have sufficient goal clarity and data access to support autonomous action</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>The use case is a conversational assistant or copilot — use ai-native-product-development instead</item>
        <item>Success criteria require a human judge ("does this feel good?") — agentic systems need machine-verifiable success conditions</item>
        <item>Organization lacks engineering maturity to build and monitor agentic pipelines</item>
        <item>Regulatory constraints require human review of every AI-generated output before it reaches users</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Traditional vs Agentic AI">
      <rule>
        <statement>Design agentic products around goal achievement, not task completion.</statement>
        <rationale>Traditional AI is user-triggered and single-model; agentic AI orchestrates multiple models toward an outcome autonomously. Measuring task completion misses whether the agent actually solved the business problem.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Key distinctions: Traditional: single model, user-triggered, task completion, static behavior. Agentic: orchestrated systems, autonomous action, goal achievement, learns from results.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic Design Principles">
      <rule>
        <statement>Define outcomes (goal states), not tasks (steps).</statement>
        <rationale>Agentic systems need a machine-verifiable definition of success to know when to stop, escalate, or retry. Describing steps instead of outcomes forces the agent into rigid scripting.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Design the human-in-the-loop model before designing the happy path.</statement>
        <rationale>40% of agentic pilots fail to productionize because they lack a production-grade escalation path. The escalation design prevents production disasters; the happy path is optimistic.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Make agentic behavior explainable: always surface the agent's reasoning to operators.</statement>
        <rationale>Unexplainable autonomous decisions block trust and regulatory approval. Explainability is a product feature, not an engineering afterthought.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Minimum Viable Intelligence (MVI)">
      <rule>
        <statement>Replace MVP with MVI for agentic products: scope on intelligence level, not feature count.</statement>
        <rationale>Feature count is a proxy for value in traditional products. For agentic products, value comes from the reliability and autonomy of the agent's decisions. An agent that handles 80% of inbound tickets reliably is more valuable than one that handles 100% poorly.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Cost range: ~$50K (MVI) to $500K+ (enterprise autonomous). Cost structure shifts from development-heavy (70% salaries) to infrastructure-heavy (60% inference + infra).</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Model Selection by Task">
      <rule>
        <statement>Match model to task complexity: haiku for pattern application, sonnet for analysis, opus for strategy.</statement>
        <rationale>Model cost is a first-class product metric for agentic systems. Overusing high-capability models on mechanical tasks erodes unit economics.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <note>Haiku for methodology implementation, Sonnet for code review, Opus for agentic strategy design.</note>
    </section>
    <section name="Required Spec Sections">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every agentic product spec must include: goal state, autonomous actions list, human-in-the-loop checkpoints, escalation triggers, success metrics, and failure modes.</statement>
        <rationale>Specs that describe agentic behavior in natural language ("the agent will handle complex cases") are not implementable. Each autonomous action must be enumerated with its triggering conditions.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Goal state: machine-verifiable definition of success (how do we know the agent succeeded?).</item>
        <item>Autonomous actions: exhaustive list of what the agent may do without user approval.</item>
        <item>Human-in-the-loop checkpoints: which actions require approval and why.</item>
        <item>Escalation triggers: conditions that pause the agent and alert a human.</item>
        <item>Success metrics: goal achievement rate, autonomy ratio, cost-per-task targets.</item>
        <item>Failure modes and recovery plan: what the agent does when it hits an edge case.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Escalation-First Rule">
      <rule>
        <statement>Write the escalation path before the happy path in the spec.</statement>
        <rationale>The happy path is optimistic and incomplete. The escalation path is what prevents production disasters and enables stakeholder trust in the autonomous system.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Spec defines the happy path in detail and notes "edge cases to be handled in v2."</description>
        <reason>Edge cases in production are not deferred — they are the failure mode. Without an escalation path, the agent will either freeze or act incorrectly on the cases that matter most.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Regulated Domains">
      <rule>
        <statement>Any agentic spec in a regulated domain (finance, health, legal) must explicitly enumerate which outputs require human sign-off before action.</statement>
        <rationale>This cannot be left as an implementation detail. Regulatory accountability requires documented human oversight points in the product spec, not the codebase.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Behavioral Regression">
      <rule>
        <statement>Version the agentic product's behavior; when the underlying model changes, run regression tests against the defined goal achievement rate and autonomy ratio thresholds.</statement>
        <rationale>Model providers update models without code releases. Agentic product behavior can change silently. Without regression tests, production incidents are detected by users, not operators.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Team upgrades to a new model version without running behavioral tests because "the model is better."</description>
        <reason>A better model on benchmark tasks may produce different outputs on the product's specific inputs. Goal achievement rate and autonomy ratio must be validated empirically before rollout.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Core Metrics">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use goal achievement rate, autonomy ratio, and cost-per-task as primary agentic product metrics — not click-through rate or cost-per-user.</statement>
        <rationale>Agentic systems scale with task volume, not seat count. Standard product metrics measure user engagement; agentic metrics measure the system's reliability and economic efficiency at accomplishing goals.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Goal achievement rate: fraction of tasks where the agent reached the defined goal state (autonomous + escalated where human approved).</item>
        <item>Autonomy ratio: fraction of tasks completed without human intervention.</item>
        <item>Failure rate: fraction of tasks that did not reach the goal state.</item>
        <item>Cost-per-task: total inference + infrastructure cost divided by tasks completed.</item>
        <item>Escalation rate: fraction of tasks that triggered a human-in-the-loop checkpoint.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Defining Intelligence Level">
      <rule>
        <statement>Define "intelligence level" in concrete, testable terms before launch, not after.</statement>
        <rationale>Vague intelligence claims ("the agent is smart") cannot be measured or improved. A testable definition ("the agent handles 80% of inbound support tickets without human review") enables sprint-over-sprint optimization.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>"The agent handles 80% of inbound support tickets without human review, achieves goal achievement rate &gt;= 0.90 across all ticket types, and costs &lt; $0.05 per ticket."</note>
      </example>
      <example type="bad">
        <note>"The agent will handle complex cases intelligently and escalate when uncertain."</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="A/B Testing for Agentic Products">
      <rule>
        <statement>Test goal achievement rate, not click-through rate. Require a 100-task pilot on real production data before committing an agentic feature to the roadmap.</statement>
        <rationale>Agentic demos use cherry-picked inputs. Success in a controlled demo does not imply a viable goal achievement rate across real production traffic. The feedback loop is longer than for UI A/B tests.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic Workflow and Subagents">
      <p>Use a product-spec subagent to draft the agentic product requirements document (goal state definition, autonomous actions list, escalation matrix, success metrics). Feed the draft to a review subagent that checks for ambiguous goal definitions, missing failure modes, and gaps in the human-in-the-loop model. A separate subagent generates the MVI scope canvas by applying the "intelligence level vs. feature count" framework: which capabilities are core intelligence, which are deferred to v2.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents: faion-mlp-agent (mode: propose) proposes WOW features that create product differentiation beyond the baseline MVI. faion-mvp-scope-analyzer-agent adapts MVP scope analysis to MVI scope; useful for understanding competitor agentic feature sets. spec-reviewer checks agentic product spec for: machine-verifiable goal state, complete autonomous action list, human-in-the-loop model, escalation triggers, and rollback plan. mvi-scoper applies the MVI framework: maps each proposed capability to an intelligence tier (core / value-add / deferred).</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Prompt Patterns">
      <example type="good" title="Agentic Product Spec Template">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[You are a product manager writing a spec for an agentic AI feature.

Feature: {feature_name}
Product goal: {goal}
Target persona: {persona}

Produce the following sections:
1. Goal state (machine-verifiable: how do we know the agent succeeded?)
2. Autonomous actions (what can the agent do without user approval?)
3. Human-in-the-loop checkpoints (which actions require approval, and why?)
4. Escalation triggers (what conditions pause the agent and alert a human?)
5. Success metrics (goal achievement rate, autonomy ratio, cost-per-task targets)
6. Failure modes and recovery plan]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Spec Review Prompt">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Review this agentic product spec for production readiness:
{spec_text}

Flag: ambiguous goal states, missing escalation triggers, undefined failure recovery,
underspecified human-in-the-loop model. Return a structured list of gaps.]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="CLI Tools and Services">
      <p>CLI tools: anthropic (Claude Agent SDK) is the underlying runtime for agentic products built on Claude. langfuse provides observability for agentic products; track goal achievement and escalation rates. temporal is a durable workflow engine — the infrastructure layer most agentic products need. linear (API) provides issue and roadmap tracking; agentic product specs live here.</p>
      <p>Services: Anthropic API (SaaS) — Claude as the reasoning engine for the agentic product. Langfuse (OSS/SaaS) — production observability: trace each agent task, measure outcome metrics. Temporal Cloud (SaaS) — durable execution for long-running agentic workflows with reliable retry. PostHog (OSS/SaaS) — product analytics: track goal achievement rate as a product metric. Linear (SaaS) — roadmap and spec management for agentic feature backlog. Notion (SaaS) — spec documentation; lacks structured review workflow for agentic specs.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <list>
        <item>Write the escalation path before the happy path in the spec — the happy path is optimistic; the escalation path is what prevents production disasters</item>
        <item>Define "intelligence level" in concrete, testable terms: "the agent handles 80% of inbound support tickets without human review" is better than "the agent is smart"</item>
        <item>Use cost-per-task as the primary efficiency metric for agentic products, not cost-per-user — agentic systems scale with task volume, not seat count</item>
        <item>Involve engineering in MVI scoping before the spec is finalized; the intelligence level you can achieve is constrained by what the current model can reliably do</item>
        <item>Version the agentic product's behavior: when the underlying model changes, test whether the goal achievement rate and autonomy ratio hold — document the acceptable regression threshold</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Critical Gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Product specs that describe agentic behavior in natural language ("the agent will handle complex cases") are not implementable; every autonomous action must be enumerated explicitly with its triggering conditions</item>
        <item>Human-in-the-loop checkpoint: any spec for an agentic product in a regulated domain (finance, health, legal) must explicitly call out which outputs require human sign-off before action — this cannot be left as an implementation detail</item>
        <item>Model capability drift: when the model provider updates a model, the agentic product's behavior may change without a code release — build behavioral regression tests that run on every model update</item>
        <item>Agentic product demos often use cherry-picked inputs; success in a controlled demo does not imply a viable goal achievement rate across real production traffic — require a 100-task pilot on real data before committing to the roadmap</item>
        <item>MVI framing focuses on "intelligence level," but what intelligence means for a specific product is rarely obvious — teams spend too long debating the definition instead of shipping</item>
        <item>Cost range ($50K–$500K+ for enterprise agentic) is a rough guide; actual cost depends heavily on the number of LLM calls per task and the per-token cost of the models chosen</item>
        <item>40% of agentic pilots fail to productionize — the failure point is usually not the model, but the lack of an error recovery path when the agent hits an edge case</item>
        <item>Model selection tables age quickly; the right model for cost management today may not be the right choice in 6 months</item>
        <item>Agentic products require a different type of A/B testing: you are testing goal achievement rate, not click-through rate, and the feedback loop is longer</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Sprint Metrics Tracking">
      <p>Use a dataclass + summary function for autonomy ratio and goal achievement rate per sprint. SprintAgentMetrics includes period, total_tasks, autonomous (completed without human intervention), escalated (required human review), and failed (did not reach goal state). The sprint_summary function returns autonomy_ratio, goal_achievement_rate, failure_rate, and cost_efficiency (tracked separately via langfuse).</p>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/sprint-metrics.py" purpose="Dataclass + summary function for autonomy ratio and goal achievement rate per sprint"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-spec-writer.txt" purpose="Prompt for drafting an agentic product requirements document"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-spec-reviewer.txt" purpose="Prompt for reviewing a spec for missing escalation triggers and failure modes"/>
    </templates>
